<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> <br>
Will This Idea Fly? <br>
President Sets His Sights on Moon, Mars <br>
Monday, January 19, 2004; Page C14 <br>
<br>
<br>
President Bush and his advisers were looking for &quot;a big idea,&quot; something the country could rally 'round. So they came up with a proposal that is, well, out of this world: Send people back to the moon and then on to Mars. <br>
<br>
  <br>
  <br>
&quot;Today I announce a new plan to explore space and extend a human presence across our solar system,&quot; the president said Wednesday at NASA headquarters in Washington. <br>
<br>
Bush's plan is obviously a big idea, but is it a good idea? Opinion polls show that a slight majority of Americans believe it would be better to spend the money on other things, such as education. An even larger percentage of people say we should send robots, not humans, into space. <br>
<br>
In outlining his lofty goals, the president appealed to Americans' spirit of adventure and promised a &quot;new era of discovery.&quot; <br>
<br>
&quot;Mankind is drawn to the heavens for the same reason we were once drawn into unknown lands and across the open sea,&quot; he said. &quot;We choose to explore space because doing so improves our lives and lifts our national spirit.&quot; <br>
<br>
Fern Shen explains what the president has in mind. <br>
<br>
What is Bush proposing? <br>
<br>
He wants Americans to return to the moon as early as 2015. That would mean phasing out NASA's aging fleet of space shuttles in favor of a powerful new rocket modeled on the 1960s Apollo spacecraft. This new Crew Exploration Vehicle would transport crews to and from the International Space Station, land on the moon and eventually take part in manned missions to Mars. A permanent station on the moon would be the staging ground for sending people to Mars and, possibly, other planets. <br>
<br>
Is the space station still in the picture? <br>
<br>
For a while. The plan calls for NASA to help finish the space station in the next five or six years. Another early project is sending robots to the moon by 2008. <br>
<br>
What will all this cost? <br>
<br>
The president proposes to give NASA a $1 billion increase over the next five years and to shift $11 billion from other space agency projects. He also will seek small annual increases in NASA's budget. Skeptics say the costs would be a lot higher. <br>
<br>
The United States last sent astronauts to the moon in 1972. Why go back now? <br>
<br>
Oddly, this idea follows last year's Columbia shuttle tragedy and findings that NASA has been badly managed. A panel that examined the space agency said it needs clear goals. The president also argued, as supporters of space programs have in the past, that his plan could lead to useful breakthroughs in communications, weather forecasting and electronics. <br>
<br>
Some people say the driving force behind the plan is political: Talking about space could give Bush's reelection campaign a boost. <br>
<br>
Is travel to Mars even doable? <br>
<br>
Scientists have much to learn and will need to develop a lot of complex technology, but yes, they think it is possible. The trip to Mars and back, with just a short stay, would take three years, some scientists say. But being mission-ready is a long way off, they caution, pointing to the difficulties the British had recently with their unmanned Beagle 2 craft. The lander reached Mars on Dec. 24 but has not &quot;phoned home&quot; since then. <br>
