<br>
This whole thing is bassackwards. Shrub doesn't have prior support of congress and the pblic, so the many comparisons to Kennedy's speech in '61 are wrong.<br>
The &quot;plan&quot; as outlined was not designed or even consulted by engineers. It's unrealistic and vague.<br>
Its vagueness destroys it: Nobody understands why it's wrong-headed in its direction, because nobody took time to widely  inform people. If a properly worked plan -like Mars Direct or something similarly focussed like an NEA version- were presented, with sure prices which utterly destroyed the (false, but it has influence) $600 billion that's being cited, then we'd have something.<br>
<br>
 If we wanted something do-ableand low risk but immensely promising, we should concentrate on the OSP non-reusable capsule and the Shuttle-C/Ares. Between the 2 of them, they keep up our commitment to the ISS (and the HST!!), and we should make sure they were properly and honestly costed rather than the typical NASA big-government graft machine.<br>
<br>
What they're proposing is a disaster for space travel.<br>
It shuts down everything we've been using for space, including all the factories and infrastructure which supports congressional districts votes  (which I don't like but that's how the country is run) and wipes the slate completely clean. It leaves nothing for us to use but completely new things, sometime in the future.<br>
Very uncertain and shaky.<br>
<br>
Better yet, to do it reasonably, safely, and cheaply, give the funding to other entities than NASA. (dreaming)<br>
Give a few hundred million to Truax for Sea Dragon (with no governmental program strings attached)<br>
Give similar funding to the Mars Society, and the Artemis Society, under condition they use Mars Direct hardware for their Lunar base. The Mars mission has no logical basis for being based on or launched from the Moon, but we should go back to the Moon anyway.<br>
